chat_history.content:
[
  {
    "day": 1,
    "focus": "Finite-volume advection basics and modified-equation intuition",
    "primary_item": "Read a compact treatment of 1D linear advection discretizations: first-order upwind, central differencing, and Lax–Wendroff, with emphasis on truncation error and numerical diffusion/dispersion.",
    "active_task": "Derive the modified equation for first-order upwind and identify the artificial diffusion term. Write 3–5 lines on when that diffusion is stabilizing versus physically damaging."
  },
  {
    "day": 2,
    "focus": "Pressure-velocity coupling on collocated grids",
    "primary_item": "Review a note or chapter section on SIMPLE/PISO-style pressure correction and why pressure checkerboarding occurs on collocated meshes.",
    "active_task": "Sketch the algorithmic sequence of one SIMPLE iteration and annotate where mass conservation is enforced only approximately. Then note where a Rhie–Chow-type interpolation enters conceptually."
  },
  {
    "day": 3,
    "focus": "Turbulence closures: eddy-viscosity assumption",
    "primary_item": "Read a turbulence-modeling section introducing the Boussinesq hypothesis and one-equation/two-equation RANS closures.",
    "active_task": "Write a short comparison of SA vs k-omega SST in terms of cost, near-wall behavior, separation sensitivity, and expected industrial robustness."
  },
  {
    "day": 4,
    "focus": "Code-oriented session: sparse linear systems",
    "primary_item": "Read documentation or a concise technical article on Krylov methods for nonsymmetric systems and practical preconditioning choices in CFD.",
    "active_task": "Implement or inspect a small GMRES/BiCGStab solve on a toy sparse system in Python/NumPy/SciPy. Record iteration count changes with and without ILU or Jacobi preconditioning."
  },
  {
    "day": 5,
    "focus": "Von Neumann stability, but only where it is actually informative",
    "primary_item": "Study stability analysis for explicit schemes on advection and diffusion equations, including the meaning and limitations of amplification-factor arguments.",
    "active_task": "Compute the CFL restriction for explicit Euler + first-order upwind and explicit Euler + second-order central on linear advection. Note why one is practically usable and the other is not."
  },
  {
    "day": 6,
    "focus": "LES filtering and subgrid-scale modeling",
    "primary_item": "Read an introductory but technical LES section: filtered Navier–Stokes equations, closure problem, and basic SGS models such as Smagorinsky/dynamic variants.",
    "active_task": "Write the filtered momentum equation and mark clearly which term becomes unclosed after filtering. Then list two reasons LES quality is strongly tied to mesh and numerics."
  },
  {
    "day": 7,
    "focus": "Quiet synthesis day",
    "primary_item": "Revisit notes from days 1–6 and select one concept that links numerics and modeling, such as how numerical dissipation can contaminate turbulence-resolution claims.",
    "active_task": "Write a one-page technical memo to yourself: 'How to distinguish physical dissipation, modeled dissipation, and numerical dissipation in practice.'"
  },
  {
    "day": 8,
    "focus": "Convection–diffusion tradeoffs and boundedness",
    "primary_item": "Read about finite-volume discretization of the steady convection–diffusion equation, including Peclet-number effects and why central differencing can fail in convection-dominated regimes.",
    "active_task": "For a 1D convection–diffusion problem, derive the coefficient signs for central differencing and identify when boundedness issues appear. Connect this to practical scheme selection."
  },
  {
    "day": 9,
    "focus": "Wall treatment in RANS and hybrid methods",
    "primary_item": "Study wall functions versus low-Re integration and, if possible, a short note on DES/IDDES-style hybridization.",
    "active_task": "Make a compact table with columns: approach, mesh requirement near wall, cost, separation handling, common failure modes."
  },
  {
    "day": 10,
    "focus": "Multigrid intuition",
    "primary_item": "Read a concise explanation of why relaxation damps high-frequency error and why coarse grids are needed for low-frequency error. Prefer geometric intuition over purely algebraic formalism, but keep it technical.",
    "active_task": "Take a simple Poisson problem and write a few lines explaining which error components Jacobi damps poorly and why multigrid changes the convergence picture qualitatively."
  },
  {
    "day": 11,
    "focus": "Limiter design and nonlinear reconstruction",
    "primary_item": "Read a section on TVD ideas, slope limiters, or MUSCL-type reconstruction for hyperbolic problems.",
    "active_task": "Compare minmod, van Leer, and superbee qualitatively in terms of dissipation, sharpness, and oscillation control. Add one sentence on where each might become too aggressive or too diffusive."
  },
  {
    "day": 12,
    "focus": "Turbulence anisotropy and model-form limitations",
    "primary_item": "Read about why linear eddy-viscosity models struggle for strongly curved, rotating, separated, or anisotropic flows.",
    "active_task": "List three flow classes where Boussinesq-based closures are structurally weak, and explain whether the issue is calibration, missing physics, or constitutive limitation."
  },
  {
    "day": 13,
    "focus": "Performance-minded scientific computing",
    "primary_item": "Read a technical article or talk on memory bandwidth, sparse-matrix assembly, cache behavior, vectorization, or MPI scaling in PDE solvers.",
    "active_task": "Profile one small kernel you already have—or imagine one, such as residual assembly or stencil update—and classify whether it is likely compute-bound or memory-bound. Justify briefly."
  },
  {
    "day": 14,
    "focus": "Integration day: from PDE to solver to interpretation",
    "primary_item": "Choose one canonical problem—lid-driven cavity, channel flow, backward-facing step, or 1D shock tube if you want something simpler—and mentally walk through the full pipeline: equations, discretization, linearization, solver, turbulence model, diagnostics.",
    "active_task": "Write a pre-run checklist with headings: physical assumptions, grid concerns, boundary conditions, discretization risks, solver settings, turbulence-model caveats, validation metrics."
  }
]

A few notes on why this should work well in that morning slot:

- Each day has a **single sharp conceptual target**, so the session stays dense without becoming sprawling.
- The active tasks force **production, not just recognition**.
- The sequence alternates between **theory, modeling, and implementation**, which should keep it from feeling like textbook grinding.

If you want, I can do one of two useful follow-ups:
1. convert this into a **resource-specific plan** with exact papers/books/lectures for each day, or
2. adapt it toward a stronger bias: **more turbulence**, **more numerics**, or **more HPC/code profiling**.
